00:05:51.590 --> 00:05:53.510
It's nice to be with you.

00:05:53.510 --> 00:06:04.500
[ Applause ]

00:06:06.080 --> 00:06:09.620
&gt;&gt; James Billington: Thank you
very much, Senator Stevens.

00:06:09.620 --> 00:06:13.950 position:56%
We meet tonight in an institution
that arose from the personal library

00:06:13.950 --> 00:06:18.400 position:56%
of the great humanist Thomas
Jefferson in a building that's named

00:06:18.400 --> 00:06:22.730
for him and has been gloriously
restored by the congress

00:06:22.730 --> 00:06:26.730 position:56%
of the United States, which created
this institution in the first place.

00:06:26.730 --> 00:06:29.320
And we are celebrating in
this ceremony the highest form

00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:34.290
of Jefferson's pursuit of
happiness, the pursuit of truth.

00:06:34.290 --> 00:06:37.370
This is the essence of
what happens in big ways

00:06:37.370 --> 00:06:39.500
and small in any library.

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:41.890
The pursuit of truth, after all,

00:06:41.890 --> 00:06:44.510
helps keep us from the
pursuit of each other.

00:06:44.510 --> 00:06:49.010
[ Laughter ]

00:06:49.010 --> 00:06:53.520
This pursuit has been the
life's work of the first scholar

00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:55.940
to be awarded this
unique international prize

00:06:55.940 --> 00:06:58.160
in the study of humanity.

00:06:58.160 --> 00:07:00.430
And, you know, it's rather
appropriate in the way

00:07:00.430 --> 00:07:04.670
that it should be someone from
Poland since people like Brzezinski

00:07:04.670 --> 00:07:09.280
and Kosciuszko were part of the
founding fathers, fought in our war

00:07:09.280 --> 00:07:12.420
of independence, and
helped bring this country

00:07:12.420 --> 00:07:14.760
into being in the first place.

00:07:14.760 --> 00:07:21.800
Kluge prize is designed with a high
level of scholarly accomplishment--

00:07:21.800 --> 00:07:25.400
and with the high level of
compensation I might add

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:28.530
of the Nobel awards--
and it fills in a gap

00:07:28.530 --> 00:07:31.890
between the national sciences that
are so well honored on the one hand

00:07:31.890 --> 00:07:34.680
of the Nobel prizes and
peace and literature,

00:07:34.680 --> 00:07:36.530
which are recognized in the others.

00:07:36.530 --> 00:07:40.140
It is for this lifetime of
achievement in the scholarship

00:07:40.140 --> 00:07:43.590
of the human condition that
this award is being made

00:07:43.590 --> 00:07:46.190
and it's appropriate, I think,
to make it in America's capital

00:07:46.190 --> 00:07:47.490
since so much scholarly work

00:07:47.490 --> 00:07:51.660
in these fields has been
done in this country.

00:07:51.660 --> 00:07:55.170
First and foremost, the criterion
we established was achievement

00:07:55.170 --> 00:07:57.450
of high distinction in
a chosen academic field

00:07:57.450 --> 00:08:00.410
as attested to by one's peers.

00:08:00.410 --> 00:08:03.180
Additional considerations
were whether--

00:08:03.180 --> 00:08:05.020
are whether or not his

00:08:05.020 --> 00:08:08.330
or her scholarly work has
also [inaudible] disciplines

00:08:08.330 --> 00:08:13.690
in a significant way and, in
some sense, the broader public

00:08:13.690 --> 00:08:16.770
of the humanity, which
is the subject of this.

00:08:16.770 --> 00:08:19.850
By all three of these, Leszek
Kolakowski emerges as a giant

00:08:19.850 --> 00:08:22.130
of the second half
of the 20th century.

00:08:22.130 --> 00:08:24.830
In a wide variety of
languages and formats,

00:08:24.830 --> 00:08:28.510
he has focused his life
on asking big questions.

00:08:28.510 --> 00:08:31.760
He is a gifted and accessible
philosopher, a theoretician

00:08:31.760 --> 00:08:36.270
of European culture, a historian
of religion, and an essayist

00:08:36.270 --> 00:08:40.620
of enormous sweep, all filled
with the gentle irony and humor

00:08:40.620 --> 00:08:44.700
that great humanists
often are able to display.

00:08:44.700 --> 00:08:50.110
And last, but by no means least,
he was a major contributor to

00:08:50.110 --> 00:08:55.750
and an intellectual inspiration for
the solidarity movement in Poland,

00:08:55.750 --> 00:09:00.090
which played such a decisive
role in the peaceful, nonviolent,

00:09:00.090 --> 00:09:03.950
and deeply democratic emergence
of Eastern Central Europe

00:09:03.950 --> 00:09:07.210
from the totalitarian system
that had been imposed on it

00:09:07.210 --> 00:09:12.470
and was long thought by many to
be a permanent system of rule.

00:09:12.470 --> 00:09:17.120 position:56%
The modern world has given birth to
something we call an intelligentsia.

00:09:17.120 --> 00:09:20.450
People of learning whose lives are
somehow set apart from the ordinary

00:09:20.450 --> 00:09:25.560
and are centered on cultivating
ideas for higher moral purposes.

00:09:25.560 --> 00:09:28.290
The word intelligentsia
arouses some suspicion

00:09:28.290 --> 00:09:31.900
in the English-speaking world
because it suggests people cut off

00:09:31.900 --> 00:09:34.820
from everyday life likely
to promote utopian ideas

00:09:34.820 --> 00:09:38.790
that could have disastrous
practical consequences.

00:09:38.790 --> 00:09:42.310
But the word intelligentsia
was, in fact, invented by Poles

00:09:42.310 --> 00:09:46.310
in the early 19th century after
they had lost their freedom.

00:09:46.310 --> 00:09:48.740
And the better anti-utopian version

00:09:48.740 --> 00:09:53.610 position:56%
of an intelligentsia played decisive
role in helping bring freedom back

00:09:53.610 --> 00:09:57.370
to Poland in the late 20th century.

00:09:57.370 --> 00:10:01.230 position:56%
Arnold Toynbee and his mighty
12-volume study of history suggested

00:10:01.230 --> 00:10:04.700
that large-scale systems of
government continue to prevail

00:10:04.700 --> 00:10:07.350
until they meet challenges
to which they cannot

00:10:07.350 --> 00:10:11.130
by their very nature find
an adequate response.

00:10:11.130 --> 00:10:14.810
The solidarity movement in Poland
was that type of challenge.

00:10:14.810 --> 00:10:19.040
It was a mass-based
religiously-grounded bottom-up

00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:24.110
nonviolent challenge to a
top-down anti-democratic elite

00:10:24.110 --> 00:10:28.070
with an atheistic etiology and
an authority based on fear.

00:10:28.070 --> 00:10:33.260
It had no way of adequately
meeting the challenge posed.

00:10:33.260 --> 00:10:34.560
The word intelligentsia

00:10:34.560 --> 00:10:37.640
in its original Polish
usage was simply taken

00:10:37.640 --> 00:10:40.940 position:56%
from the Latin word for intelligent.

00:10:40.940 --> 00:10:45.960
And Leszek Kolakowski embodies that
quality and he spoke more clearly

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:48.830
and more influentially
to the intelligence

00:10:48.830 --> 00:10:52.570
of the rising better-educated
generation in Poland

00:10:52.570 --> 00:10:54.320
than any other single figure.

00:10:54.320 --> 00:10:57.710
He was the voice of hope
that helped free people

00:10:57.710 --> 00:11:00.450
from the paralysis of fear.

00:11:00.450 --> 00:11:02.980
The chain of events that
down the communist system

00:11:02.980 --> 00:11:06.490
in Eastern Europe began in Poland
with a movement inspired both

00:11:06.490 --> 00:11:12.920
by religious faith, of which
Kolakowski has made studies as deep

00:11:12.920 --> 00:11:15.690 position:56%
as any European scholar of his time,

00:11:15.690 --> 00:11:20.430
and also by straightforward human
enlightened intelligence applied

00:11:20.430 --> 00:11:25.000
to inhuman social realities,
which Kolakowski performed

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:28.030
with elegance and significance.

00:11:28.030 --> 00:11:33.450
In the words of the-- one of
the great leaders of solidarity,

00:11:33.450 --> 00:11:37.140
Bronislaw Geremek, who later
became foreign minister of Poland--

00:11:37.140 --> 00:11:41.860
and I'm quoting this, which is,
I think, the right introduction.

00:11:41.860 --> 00:11:45.770
We have, incidentally, a formal
citation, which I'm not going

00:11:45.770 --> 00:11:49.550
to read, but I think these
words speak eloquently.

00:11:49.550 --> 00:11:54.110 position:56%
He said Leszek Kolakowski's work had
an influence on the course of events

00:11:54.110 --> 00:11:56.840
that is difficult to overestimate.

00:11:56.840 --> 00:12:00.500
His work achieved that fulfillment
which is the eternal dream

00:12:00.500 --> 00:12:04.690
of philosophers and the
ambition of intellectuals.

00:12:04.690 --> 00:12:08.470
To influence the fate of the world
and further people's aspirations

00:12:08.470 --> 00:12:12.410
of freedom, it accompanied
resistance to repression

00:12:12.410 --> 00:12:16.140
and dictatorship in Eastern and
Central Europe at every stage.

00:12:16.140 --> 00:12:19.490
This skeptical student
of enlightenment,

00:12:19.490 --> 00:12:22.790
this scholar of the
highest intellectual rigor,

00:12:22.790 --> 00:12:25.610
this opponent of all
illusions played

00:12:25.610 --> 00:12:29.210
that most romantic and
promethean of roles.

00:12:29.210 --> 00:12:33.430
He was the awakener of human hopes.

00:12:34.660 --> 00:12:37.380
Kolakowski was asked in
an interview recently what

00:12:37.380 --> 00:12:40.490
of his many achievements
he was most proud of.

00:12:40.490 --> 00:12:44.020
And he said, with his
characteristic modesty,

00:12:44.020 --> 00:12:48.130
simplicity of great
philosophers, I'm not proud.

00:12:48.130 --> 00:12:52.900 position:56%
If there is any doubt that the study
of humanity can help do great things

00:12:52.900 --> 00:12:55.960
for humanity without
violence and with out--

00:12:55.960 --> 00:13:01.010
from one dogmatism to another,
he stands before us tonight.

00:13:01.010 --> 00:13:06.860 position:56%
The man who is not proud, but of
whom we at the Library of Congress--

00:13:06.860 --> 00:13:11.180
and I think all of us here--
are very proud and grateful--

00:13:11.180 --> 00:13:15.940
have every reason to be,
since we are hailing him

00:13:15.940 --> 00:13:19.430
as the first recipient of this
prize in the human sciences

00:13:19.430 --> 00:13:23.520
for a lifetime of rare achievement.

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:26.770
We are going to bring out-- in
just a moment, we will present him

00:13:26.770 --> 00:13:30.370
