00:22:29.660 --> 00:22:31.540
It won't be long, I promise.

00:22:31.540 --> 00:22:36.620
And there is something
which has a title--

00:22:36.620 --> 00:22:44.500
has a title-- what the past is for.

00:22:44.500 --> 00:22:46.920
What the past is for.

00:22:46.920 --> 00:22:53.630
So, I start with a few
words about the future.

00:22:53.630 --> 00:22:57.260
And this futurology.

00:22:57.260 --> 00:23:03.580
According to my definition,

00:23:03.580 --> 00:23:12.120
futurology is an extremely serious
science whose subject not only is

00:23:12.120 --> 00:23:16.670
nonexistent, but necessarily
nonexistent.

00:23:16.670 --> 00:23:22.990
That is to say it-- the future
does not exist and never will,

00:23:22.990 --> 00:23:27.110
which is a common-sense remark.

00:23:27.110 --> 00:23:32.340
But we have a science about
this nonexistent subject.

00:23:32.340 --> 00:23:41.960
Well, perhaps we would
not find this worrying

00:23:41.960 --> 00:23:47.480
if it did not immediately bring
to our attention an analogous

00:23:47.480 --> 00:23:51.200
but much more terrifying insight.

00:23:51.200 --> 00:23:56.450
Mainly that the past
doesn't exist either.

00:23:56.450 --> 00:24:01.520
From the time Saint Augustine
and his classic reflections

00:24:01.520 --> 00:24:05.370
on the subject, the
mystery of time is absurd

00:24:05.370 --> 00:24:10.980
and its tormented nearly
all major philosophers

00:24:10.980 --> 00:24:15.250
up to Bergson, Husserl, and Sartre.

00:24:15.250 --> 00:24:23.490
The past, by definition, is an
ocean of events that once happened

00:24:23.490 --> 00:24:29.170
and this-- and those events are
either retained in our memory

00:24:29.170 --> 00:24:37.040
or so that they exist only as
part of our psychological reality

00:24:37.040 --> 00:24:44.270
or they are reconstructed by us on
the basis of our present experience

00:24:44.270 --> 00:24:48.020
and it is only this
present experience,

00:24:48.020 --> 00:24:52.960
our present reconstruction
of the past, that is real.

00:24:52.960 --> 00:24:55.980
Not the past as such.

00:24:55.980 --> 00:25:01.460 position:56%
In other words, the entire
[inaudible] of the past exists only,

00:25:01.460 --> 00:25:08.860 position:56%
it seems, as a portion of our-- more
strictly, of my own-- consciousness.

00:25:08.860 --> 00:25:13.840
The past in itself is nothing.

00:25:13.840 --> 00:25:21.130
This argument can strike
us as a kind of sophistry

00:25:21.130 --> 00:25:27.680
or a bizarre philosophical
exercise, but it's not so.

00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:29.380
It's not sophistry.

00:25:29.380 --> 00:25:31.390
It is serious.

00:25:31.390 --> 00:25:40.910
However, we can also look at
the question from another angle.

00:25:40.910 --> 00:25:48.520
Everything we see or touch is
obviously a product of events

00:25:48.520 --> 00:25:54.050
that had happened once,
perhaps 10 seconds ago,

00:25:54.050 --> 00:25:57.330
perhaps 10 million years ago.

00:25:57.330 --> 00:26:03.070
It is not-- is it not therefore
proper and reasonable to say

00:26:03.070 --> 00:26:09.350
that whoever we see
or touch is the past?

00:26:09.350 --> 00:26:15.080
In metaphysical terms, the
past is perhaps nothing; but,

00:26:15.080 --> 00:26:21.130
in terms of our direct
experience, the past is everything.

00:26:21.130 --> 00:26:27.460
Our entire knowledge of the
so-called external world is nothing

00:26:27.460 --> 00:26:31.930
but a continuous, uninterrupted
stream

00:26:31.930 --> 00:26:39.000
of acts whereby what was
the past becomes present.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:47.440
Yes, we may say that far from being
nothing, the past is everything.

00:26:47.440 --> 00:26:53.360
And the enigma is time is not
just something philosophers have

00:26:53.360 --> 00:26:56.820
constructed to amuse themselves.

00:26:56.820 --> 00:27:02.080
We-- when they try to
unravel its mysteries.

00:27:02.080 --> 00:27:05.640
No. The mysteries are
accessible to everyone.

00:27:05.640 --> 00:27:08.740
And so, of course,
not everyone likes

00:27:08.740 --> 00:27:13.250
to spend time in thinking
about time.

00:27:13.250 --> 00:27:20.780
It is only philosophers who try to
express this everyday experience.

00:27:20.780 --> 00:27:23.770
So, now the digression.

00:27:23.770 --> 00:27:27.340
Philosopher is not
there to be liked.

00:27:27.340 --> 00:27:29.930
It's not to like them.

00:27:29.930 --> 00:27:35.490
I remember a colleague of mine,
a professor of philosophy,

00:27:35.490 --> 00:27:41.190
telling me about his six-year-old
son who was the first time

00:27:41.190 --> 00:27:48.710
in the school and the teacher asked
all the children to say their names

00:27:48.710 --> 00:27:54.400
and then to ask what their father--
what their fathers were doing

00:27:54.400 --> 00:27:59.490
and the boy refused to say
anything and the teacher was angry.

00:27:59.490 --> 00:28:04.260
And later, at home, he explained
but I couldn't tell them

00:28:04.260 --> 00:28:10.260 position:56%
that my dad is a philosopher because
all the children would laugh at me.

00:28:10.260 --> 00:28:15.480
And, indeed, they would
have laughed at him.

00:28:15.480 --> 00:28:23.590
But, if the boy had said that his
father was, say, a circus clown,

00:28:23.590 --> 00:28:27.420
they would have laughed as well.

00:28:27.420 --> 00:28:34.290
Even so, it is a nice, respectable
job to be a circus clown.

00:28:34.290 --> 00:28:38.230
Moreover, they would have
laughed if the boy had said

00:28:38.230 --> 00:28:42.570
that his dad was a
garbage collector,

00:28:42.570 --> 00:28:46.150
even though the profession

00:28:46.150 --> 00:28:50.000
of garbage collector is
not only respectable,

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:54.910
but it's one of the most
important in today's world.

00:28:54.910 --> 00:29:00.180
Without garbage collectors,
we would not survive for long.

00:29:00.180 --> 00:29:06.670
And so, in matters of
philosophy, let us not rely

00:29:06.670 --> 00:29:10.720
on the opinions of those kids.

00:29:10.720 --> 00:29:14.170
One might add-- one might
add that the profession

00:29:14.170 --> 00:29:19.880
of a philosopher has
a significant affinity

00:29:19.880 --> 00:29:25.090
with the two professions I've just
mentioned, that of a circus clown

00:29:25.090 --> 00:29:26.870
and that of a garbage collector.

00:29:26.870 --> 00:29:30.960
But this was a digression.

00:29:30.960 --> 00:29:38.230
Let's go back to the
problem of the past.

00:29:38.230 --> 00:29:45.300
So, our direct experience may be
plausibly interpreted as a form

00:29:45.300 --> 00:29:52.360 position:56%
of contact with the past, but we can
also speak of knowledge of the past

00:29:52.360 --> 00:29:59.510
in a more specific sense, mainly
our knowledge of human history.

00:29:59.510 --> 00:30:05.680
And we may ask what this kind
of knowledge of the past is for.

00:30:05.680 --> 00:30:08.610
In the tradition of
the enlightenment,

00:30:08.610 --> 00:30:15.320 position:56%
we sometimes find a kind of
disrespect for historical knowledge.

00:30:15.320 --> 00:30:21.250
Either because history, more often
than not, is an infinite display

00:30:21.250 --> 00:30:24.720
of human stupidity and cruelty

00:30:24.720 --> 00:30:30.850
or because nothing profitable can
be learned from what mankind was

00:30:30.850 --> 00:30:37.070
up to earlier or else because
history is not a science.

00:30:37.070 --> 00:30:45.080
It is indeed arguable that we
cannot use historical knowledge

00:30:45.080 --> 00:30:51.520
to help in our present work.

00:30:51.520 --> 00:30:56.530
It's not a technical help
we can expect from it.

00:30:56.530 --> 00:30:58.170
It may be true.

00:30:58.170 --> 00:31:07.310
It may be true that whatever people
know about say military exploits

00:31:07.310 --> 00:31:12.920
of Alexander the Great or
Hannibal would not be of much use

00:31:12.920 --> 00:31:20.020
in improving the skills of today's
generals and that knowledge,

00:31:20.020 --> 00:31:24.300
say of the political intrigues
of the French Royal Court

00:31:24.300 --> 00:31:28.790
in the 17th century
would not be of much help

00:31:28.790 --> 00:31:31.960
to contemporary politicians.

00:31:31.960 --> 00:31:38.740
However, the limited
technical support to be gained

00:31:38.740 --> 00:31:43.300
from an acquaintance with the
historical events is not a good

00:31:43.300 --> 00:31:49.910 position:56%
reason for concluding that therefore
historical knowledge is irrelevant

00:31:49.910 --> 00:31:52.610
to our life.

00:31:52.610 --> 00:32:00.400
We are, of course, the cultural--
though not necessarily physical--

00:32:00.400 --> 00:32:06.040
heirs of Alexander the Great,
Hannibal, and French monarchs.

00:32:06.040 --> 00:32:10.860
Not to say that their life,
their deeds or misdeeds--

00:32:10.860 --> 00:32:15.770
not the reason that they
do not matter to our life.

00:32:15.770 --> 00:32:21.640
To say so would be almost as silly
as saying that it would not matter

00:32:21.640 --> 00:32:25.610
to me if I were suddenly to erase

00:32:25.610 --> 00:32:32.370
from my memory my own past personal
life just because, obviously,

00:32:32.370 --> 00:32:36.170
I live in the present,
not in the past.

00:32:36.170 --> 00:32:42.460
The history of prior generations is
our history and we need to know it

00:32:42.460 --> 00:32:49.080
in order to be aware of our
identity in the same sense

00:32:49.080 --> 00:32:54.040
in which my own memory
builds my personal identity.

00:32:54.040 --> 00:32:56.360
Makes me a human subject.

00:32:56.360 --> 00:33:02.540
So, we learn history in
order to know who we are.

00:33:02.540 --> 00:33:09.320 position:56%
From that assumption that history
is not a science, but rather an art,

00:33:09.320 --> 00:33:12.470
it does not follow of
course it is not interesting

00:33:12.470 --> 00:33:17.140
or unworthy of being cultivated.

00:33:17.140 --> 00:33:18.440
Obviously not.

00:33:18.440 --> 00:33:24.420
So, but here's a trivial point.

00:33:24.420 --> 00:33:29.150
But saying that history is
not a science may suggest

00:33:29.150 --> 00:33:34.880
like that unlike the natural
sciences it simply does not try

00:33:34.880 --> 00:33:39.730
to establish general laws,
but is concerned only

00:33:39.730 --> 00:33:45.170
with particular events,
unique and unrepeatable.

00:33:45.170 --> 00:33:50.230
This question has been
discussed since the 19th century.

00:33:50.230 --> 00:33:55.590
It resulted in the well-known
distinction made by Rickert

00:33:55.590 --> 00:34:01.520
between nomothetic and
ideographic disciplines.

00:34:01.520 --> 00:34:08.120
Between disciplines in which laws
are discovered and disciplines

00:34:08.120 --> 00:34:15.270
which are just concerned with the
narration of single occurrences.

00:34:15.270 --> 00:34:21.540 position:56%
In fact, yes, there is no such thing
as the laws of history in the sense

00:34:21.540 --> 00:34:29.130
of true and justifiable statements
that would tell us what--

00:34:29.130 --> 00:34:35.710 position:56%
that tell us in what certain
well-defined conditions some certain

00:34:35.710 --> 00:34:41.340
well-defined phenomena
necessarily invariably occur.

00:34:41.340 --> 00:34:48.470
The belief in laws of history was
a Hegelian or Marxian delusion.

00:34:48.470 --> 00:34:55.830
Human history is a collection of
unpredictable accidents and each

00:34:55.830 --> 00:35:05.640
of us can easily cite any number
of instances where an event

00:35:05.640 --> 00:35:10.890
that was clearly decisive in
shaping the history of mankind

00:35:10.890 --> 00:35:15.740
for subsequent decades,
centuries, could have gone

00:35:15.740 --> 00:35:18.600
in different way than it did.

00:35:18.600 --> 00:35:21.320
There was no-- there
was no necessity

00:35:21.320 --> 00:35:29.720
in its happening or in its result.

00:35:29.720 --> 00:35:37.230
The phrase the laws of history has
also been used to describe tendency

00:35:37.230 --> 00:35:43.570
or trends that are bound to
prevail in the near future.

00:35:43.570 --> 00:35:49.990
This use was particularly
frequent in Marxist doctrine

00:35:49.990 --> 00:35:57.240 position:56%
and its ideological meaning calls
that future events could be foreseen

00:35:57.240 --> 00:36:01.960
on the allegedly scientific basis.

00:36:01.960 --> 00:36:09.470
Alas, all the predictions
made by Marx or later by--

00:36:09.470 --> 00:36:17.260
or by later Marxists-- all of
them that were demonstrably false.

00:36:17.260 --> 00:36:23.260
So far, development went in an
entirely different direction.

00:36:23.260 --> 00:36:29.140 position:56%
The middle classes, instead of
gradually shrinking and disappearing

00:36:29.140 --> 00:36:34.250
as the Marxist prophecy
would have it, grew and grew.

00:36:34.250 --> 00:36:40.460
The market, far from being an
obstacle to technological progress,

00:36:40.460 --> 00:36:47.030
as Marxists claimed, proved to
be its more powerful stimulus.

00:36:47.030 --> 00:36:50.410
The relative and absolute
popularization

00:36:50.410 --> 00:36:55.350
of the working class
failed to occur.

00:36:55.350 --> 00:37:01.310
The falling rate of profit, which
was supposed to be the cause

00:37:01.310 --> 00:37:07.140
of collapse of capitalism
proved vain hope.

00:37:07.140 --> 00:37:12.140
The proletarian revolution,
it is revolution resulting

00:37:12.140 --> 00:37:17.170
from the conflict between
industrial workers of capitalism.

00:37:17.170 --> 00:37:20.820
This revolution never happened.

00:37:20.820 --> 00:37:25.660
The Russian revolution was
in a way an example of it.

00:37:25.660 --> 00:37:33.320
What perhaps comes-- came-- came
the closest to such a revolution,

00:37:33.320 --> 00:37:37.960
at least conceptually-- that was
perhaps the worker's movement

00:37:37.960 --> 00:37:41.130
in Poland in the early 80's.

00:37:41.130 --> 00:37:47.320
As this movement, it was
directed against a socialist state

00:37:47.320 --> 00:37:53.850
and carried under the sign of
cross was the blessing pope.

00:37:53.850 --> 00:37:58.020 position:56%
So much for [inaudible] predictions.

00:37:58.020 --> 00:38:03.000
One may say that, in general,
futurology, so-called,

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:08.120
is not unhealthy state and
this for a number of reason.

00:38:08.120 --> 00:38:14.520
But there's another important way
in which the nihilistic approach

00:38:14.520 --> 00:38:18.170
to history is expressed today.

00:38:18.170 --> 00:38:24.650 position:56%
There is a post-[inaudible]
phrase, also known as postmodernism,

00:38:24.650 --> 00:38:31.800
and it says there are no
facts, only interpretations.

00:38:31.800 --> 00:38:37.300
This is in-- in the one sense,
it is trivially true and,

00:38:37.300 --> 00:38:42.540
in another sense, it is
absurd and dangerous.

00:38:42.540 --> 00:38:47.450
It is trivially true that
any description of a fact--

00:38:47.450 --> 00:38:53.990
even the simplest-- involves the
entire history of human character.

00:38:53.990 --> 00:39:04.960
When I say, for instance, this
morning, on October 29, 2003,

00:39:04.960 --> 00:39:08.190
I ate yogurt for breakfast.

00:39:08.190 --> 00:39:14.240
My words encompass the entire
history of the European calendar

00:39:14.240 --> 00:39:17.250
with all its arbitrariness.

00:39:17.250 --> 00:39:23.250 position:56%
They encompass the concept of
breakfast and the concept of yogurt,

00:39:23.250 --> 00:39:26.520
which are all human inventions.

00:39:26.520 --> 00:39:32.770
The language I use is a product of
human history and, in this sense,

00:39:32.770 --> 00:39:36.950
whenever we use it,
we interpret the word.

00:39:36.950 --> 00:39:42.270
The word never shows itself
to us, so to say directly,

00:39:42.270 --> 00:39:46.630
so to say stripped and
naked in its purity.

00:39:46.630 --> 00:39:50.920
We always perceive it
mediated by our culture,

00:39:50.920 --> 00:39:54.440
our history, our language.

00:39:54.440 --> 00:40:01.000
But this saying that there are
no facts, only interpretations,

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:05.400
has another and dangerous meaning.

00:40:05.400 --> 00:40:10.310
Since historical knowledge
is supposed to consist

00:40:10.310 --> 00:40:16.110
in the description of facts,
of things that really happened,

00:40:16.110 --> 00:40:22.830
the idea that there are no facts
in the normal sense implies--

00:40:22.830 --> 00:40:27.010
this idea implies that
interpretations do not depend

00:40:27.010 --> 00:40:30.020
on facts, but the other way around.

00:40:30.020 --> 00:40:35.520
The facts are produced
by interpretations.

00:40:35.520 --> 00:40:40.770
Let us suppose that I stole
a bottle of wine from a shop.

00:40:40.770 --> 00:40:43.910
The saying, Mr. K stole a bottle

00:40:43.910 --> 00:40:49.620
of wine would be an interpretation
which generates a fact.

00:40:49.620 --> 00:40:52.840
The fact in itself does not exist.

00:40:52.840 --> 00:40:59.900
Consequently, phrases like Mr. K is
guilty of stealing a bottle of wine

00:40:59.900 --> 00:41:02.650
or Mr. K should be punished

00:41:02.650 --> 00:41:07.360
for his crime have no
meaning in relation to a fact.

00:41:07.360 --> 00:41:11.950
They are just parts
of the interpretation.

00:41:11.950 --> 00:41:16.250
In other words, the
concept of modern judgment

00:41:16.250 --> 00:41:21.870
and therefore also the concept
of good and evil are empty.

00:41:21.870 --> 00:41:25.870
They don't refer to
an empirical reality,

00:41:25.870 --> 00:41:30.030
but only to our way of
judging the reality.

00:41:30.030 --> 00:41:35.470
Judging according to an a
priori conceptual [inaudible].

00:41:35.470 --> 00:41:46.730
The doctrine that there are no
facts, only interpretations,

00:41:46.730 --> 00:41:54.060 position:56%
in fact, abolishes the idea of human
responsibility and moral judgements.

00:41:54.060 --> 00:42:00.140
Moreover, in effect, it considers
any myth, any legend or fable just

00:42:00.140 --> 00:42:06.160
as valid in terms of knowledge
as any fact that we have verified

00:42:06.160 --> 00:42:11.930
as being verified as such according

00:42:11.930 --> 00:42:16.020
to the standards of
historical inquiry.

00:42:16.020 --> 00:42:23.310
In epistemological terms, any
mythical theory is just as good

00:42:23.310 --> 00:42:27.190
as any historical established fact.

00:42:27.190 --> 00:42:33.230
The story of Hercules fighting
against Hydra is not worse,

00:42:33.230 --> 00:42:37.300
not less true in historical
terms than the history

00:42:37.300 --> 00:42:41.710
of Napoleon being defeated
at Waterloo.

00:42:41.710 --> 00:42:45.820
There are not valid rules
for establishing truth,

00:42:45.820 --> 00:42:50.980
consequently there is
not such thing as truths.

00:42:50.980 --> 00:42:53.150
There is no need to elaborate

00:42:53.150 --> 00:42:57.880
on the disastrous cultural
effect of such a theory.

00:42:57.880 --> 00:43:06.300
Now, the upfront of my
remarks is, in fact, banal.

00:43:06.300 --> 00:43:12.210
Also, the legacy of myths
is certainly an important

00:43:12.210 --> 00:43:17.280 position:56%
and fertile source in human culture.

00:43:17.280 --> 00:43:23.670
We must defend and support simply
traditional research methods

00:43:23.670 --> 00:43:30.700
elaborated over century-- centuries
and establish the factual cause

00:43:30.700 --> 00:43:35.940
of history and separated
from fantasies.

00:43:35.940 --> 00:43:42.490
However, narrating those
fantasies might be the doctrine

00:43:42.490 --> 00:43:46.540
that there are no facts,
only interpretations,

00:43:46.540 --> 00:43:50.570
should be rejected as obscurantist.

00:43:50.570 --> 00:43:58.990 position:56%
And we much perceive-- prevent-- we
must preserve our traditional belief

00:43:58.990 --> 00:44:01.090
that the history of mankind--

00:44:01.090 --> 00:44:05.500
the history of things
that really happened--

00:44:05.500 --> 00:44:10.160
woven of numerable unique
accidents is the history

00:44:10.160 --> 00:44:14.120
of each of us human subjects.

00:44:14.120 --> 00:44:21.210
Whereas the belief in historical
laws is a figment of imagination.

00:44:21.210 --> 00:44:27.060
Historical knowledge, obviously,
is crucial to each of us.

00:44:27.060 --> 00:44:29.500
To schoolchildren and students.

00:44:29.500 --> 00:44:31.150
To young and old.

00:44:31.150 --> 00:44:38.840
We must absorb history as our own,
with all its horrors and tragedies

00:44:38.840 --> 00:44:43.220
as well as its beauty and splendor.

00:44:43.220 --> 00:44:47.400
It's cruelties and
persecutions as well

00:44:47.400 --> 00:44:52.800
as all the magnificent works
of human mind and hand.

00:44:52.800 --> 00:44:59.220
We must do this if we are to know
the proper place in our universe.

00:44:59.220 --> 00:45:03.830
To know who we are
and how we should act.

00:45:03.830 --> 00:45:11.040
One might-- one might ask what the
point of repeating such banalities.

00:45:11.040 --> 00:45:15.510
The answer is simply that
it is important to keep

00:45:15.510 --> 00:45:19.650
on repeating them again
and again because this--

00:45:19.650 --> 00:45:25.850
our banalities we often find
it convenient to forget.

00:45:25.850 --> 00:45:30.840
And if we forget them and
if they fall into oblivion,

00:45:30.840 --> 00:45:36.940
we'll be condemning our culture--
that's to say our sense--

00:45:36.940 --> 00:45:41.380
to ultimate and irrevocable ruin.

00:45:41.380 --> 00:45:43.070
That's all I wanted to say.

00:45:43.070 --> 00:45:46.510
Thank you very much
for your patience.

